### DSL Basics in Kotlin

Kotlin's language features -- lambdas with receivers, extension functions, infix notation, and operator overloading -- make it ideal for building type-safe Domain-Specific Languages (DSLs).

---

### What is a DSL?

A DSL is a specialized mini-language designed for a specific task. Kotlin enables internal DSLs that leverage the host language syntax.

---

### Building a Simple HTML DSL

```kotlin
fun html(init: HTML.() -> Unit): HTML {
    val html = HTML()
    html.init()
    return html
}

class HTML {
    private val children = mutableListOf<Element>()

    fun body(init: Body.() -> Unit) {
        val body = Body()
        body.init()
        children.add(body)
    }

    override fun toString() = children.joinToString("")
}

class Body {
    private val elements = mutableListOf<String>()

    fun h1(text: String) {
        elements.add("<h1>$text</h1>")
    }

    fun p(text: String) {
        elements.add("<p>$text</p>")
    }

    override fun toString() = "<body>${elements.joinToString("")}</body>"
}
```

---

### Using the DSL

```kotlin
fun main() {
    val page = html {
        body {
            h1("Welcome")
            p("This is a DSL example")
        }
    }
    println(page)
    // <body><h1>Welcome</h1><p>This is a DSL example</p></body>
}
```

---

### DSL with Infix Functions

```kotlin
infix fun String.should(be: String) {
    println("Assert: $this should be $be")
}

fun main() {
    "Kotlin" should "awesome"
}
```

---

### Type-Safe Builders

Kotlin's `@DslMarker` annotation prevents accidental scope leakage.

```kotlin
@DslMarker
annotation class HtmlDsl

@HtmlDsl
class Table {
    fun tr(init: Tr.() -> Unit) { /* ... */ }
}

@HtmlDsl
class Tr {
    fun td(init: Td.() -> Unit) { /* ... */ }
}
```

---

### Popular Kotlin DSL Examples

| DSL | Purpose |
|-----|---------|
| Ktor | HTTP client/routes |
| kotlinx.html | HTML generation |
| Gradle Kotlin DSL | Build configuration |
| Exposed | SQL queries |
| Anko | Android layouts |

> **Key Point:** DSLs in Kotlin use lambda with receiver (`T.() -> Unit`) to create a context scope. Extension functions and infix notation make DSLs feel natural.

codeExample:
class Greeter {
    private val greetings = mutableListOf<String>()

    infix fun String.says(message: String) {
        greetings.add("$this says: $message")
    }

    override fun toString() = greetings.joinToString("\n")
}

fun greet(init: Greeter.() -> Unit): Greeter {
    val greeter = Greeter()
    greeter.init()
    return greeter
}

fun main() {
    val result = greet {
        "Alice" says "Hello"
        "Bob" says "Hi"
    }
    println(result)
}
